n, mythology, the Homeric epics, tragic and comic drama, philosophy, and the city-state, the book offers shifting perspectives on an extraordinary and astonishingly creative people. Century after century, in one medium after another, the Greeks addressed big questions, many of which are still very much with us, from whether gods exist and what happens after we die to what political system is best and how we can know what is real. Yet for all their virtues, Greek men set themselves apart from women and foreigners and profited from the unpaid labor of enslaved workers, and the book also looks at the mixed legacy of the ancient Greeks today.The result is a rich, wide-ranging, and compelling history of a fascinating and profoundly influential culture in all its complexity—and the myriad ways, good and bad, it continues to shape us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMongolsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aAfterlife.  aAristophanes.  aAristotle.  aAthens.  aClassical.  aComedy.  aDemocracy.  aFestival.  aGods.  aGreece.  aHellenistic.  aHomer.  aJennifer T. Roberts.  aMisogyny.  aMythology.  aOut of One, Many: Ancient Greek Ways of Thought and Culture.  aPhilosophy.  aPlato.  aPolis.  aRape (unless you think best not).  aReligion.  aSacrifice.  aSparta.  aStoicism.  aTragedy.  aTroy.  aUnderworld.1 aRoberts, Jennifer T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691243856?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691243856423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691243856/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles